	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I mostly solo'd my way to level 16.&nbsp;&nbsp;I group pretty much when I feel like it.  Lately, I have been grouping in Crushbone because the throne room is too tough to solo - but the loot and XP are real nice.  I do solo orc legionaires outside the TR.  They con blue and are pretty easy for a level 16 rogue.  I use a Faded Shadow Rapier and a Dragoon Dirk.  For armor I have mostly Banded with a couple of extras. Wisps are great for soloing if you have a magic weapon or two and are at least level 12.<br><br>My next soloing attempt will be Dagnor's Cauldron.  I want to team up with someone and get Barnacle Bones.  He drops a decent piercer sometimes, I am told.<br><br>Soloing requires the use of 'stealth mode' (Hide+Sneak) to get behind your opponent for that opening backstab.  Since this form of travel is slow a SOW is recommended. Stick with blues and high greens below level 17.  Otherwise, the beasties can deal out damage faster than you.  Watch out for casters.  If you must fight one use the backstab skill like a bash to interrupt their casting.  It doesn't always work but its better than nothing.  Get the weapons that have the best damage/delay ratio you can afford.  A Polished Granite Tomahawk is not necessary but really nice to have if you solo.  Make sure you don't pull a train.  Don't try to take on more than one blue at a time.  2 or 3 greens should be safe.  2 blues might be possible but you will be hurting when you're done.<br><br>When selling to vendors always /CON first.  If they are not at least indifferent then use 'stealth mode' and sneak up behind them. Then open the trading window.  They will deal with you as 'indifferent' when they may not normally deal with you at all.<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
